<div style="margin:0px 10px 20px 0px;background-color:#f0f0f0;padding:5px;100%">
Review by

<a href="Collaborators.asp?id=440"><strong>Chris S</strong></a>

<br><font color="#dc143c"><strong>SPECIAL COLLABORATOR</strong> <em>H&#111;norary Collaborator</em></font>


<div style="color:#333;margin-top:5px;">

<div class="avatarhp-box">
<a href="https://www.progarchives.com/Collaborators.asp?id=440">

<img src="https://www.progarchives.com/forum/uploads/440/solidair.jpg" class="avatarhp" width=100 onerror="this.src='/forum/avatars/blank_avatar.jpg'" />
</a>
</div>

<img src="static-images/4stars.gif" alt="4 stars" border="0">
Great band from a great era. Ian Gillan, Blackmore and co had a near perfect fit and 
combination of sounds which IMO came to full force on Machine Head. The 
legendary 'Smoke On The Water' and the equally fulfilling ' Highway Star' are just two great 
songs that contribute to the album's hard rock sound. There are comparisons to Bad 
Company but with more edge, steel, grit and less laid back American Rock. True brit hard 
rock for sure.' Space Truckin' is another great track and we had another few great albums 
to go before Gillan's voice began to falter. Machine Head warrants a solid 4 stars.</strong></strong></em></em>
</div>




<p class="review-footer">
